To answer your question, you could do that. You should just know that `type` of `ShapeProps` can be `&#39;broken&#39; | &#39;curve&#39; | &#39;circle&#39; | &#39;test&#39;`. Also, since they have common attributes, why don&#39;t you move those to `ShapeBase` as follows

```typescript

interface ShapeBase&lt;T, S&gt; { 
    fill: string; 
    stroke: string; 
    type: T; 
    style: S; 
}

type LineType = &#39;broken&#39; | &#39;curve&#39;;

type LineStyle = &#39;dash&#39; | &#39;dot&#39; | &#39;line&#39;;

interface ShapeLine extends ShapeBase&lt;LineType, LineStyle&gt; { }

type PointType = &#39;circle&#39; | &#39;rect&#39;;

type PointStyle = &#39;hollow&#39; | &#39;solid&#39;;

interface ShapePoint extends ShapeBase&lt;PointType, PointStyle&gt; { }

type ShapeProps = ShapeLine | ShapePoint;

```

If there is another interface which does not have `type` nor `style`, there are two things you could do

1- Create another interface without `&lt;T, U&gt;` and make `ShapeBase` extend this new interface.

2- You can `Omit` some attributes from any interface

`type TypelessShape = Omit&lt;ShapeBase&lt;&#39;&#39;, &#39;&#39;&gt;, &#39;type&#39; | &#39;style&#39;&gt;;`

